[STEP 13] 2026-02-19 — explain02.html (standalone, plain language, proof vs verify)
- Created work/explain02.html: single file consolidating explain.html + explain01.html; written for readers with no advanced maths.
- Content: problem (3D pomegranate, higher dimensions); three sources of human value (historical / problem / game-AI) with labels; why hard (plain language); PackingStar what it is and where it came from (cosine matrix, two players, fragments); new section “Can AI prove the result is correct?”:
  - (1) Verification: yes—AI/code can check that a given arrangement is valid (no overlap, all touch centre); team does this with verify_coordinates.py, verify_cosmatrix.py; configs in official databases.
  - (2) Proving optimality: no—PackingStar does not prove “no larger arrangement exists”; that requires a logical argument over all possibilities; paper states “rigorous mathematical proof still lacking.”
- New section “Other AI tools that can help with proof”: AlphaProof (DeepMind, formal proofs in Lean), Lean / Isabelle / Coq (proof assistants), Lean Copilot (LLM-assisted proof steps); note that such tools could in future help turn human arguments into machine-checked proofs for optimality.
- Letter outline and draft updated: AI can verify a configuration is valid; proving it’s the best possible still needs humans (and possibly AlphaProof/Lean in future); draft ~148 words including this point.

